==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1610's.
* From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|accretio|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad||to|lang=la}} + {{term/t|la|crēscō||grow}}.
* Compare [[crescent]], [[increase]], [[accrue]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|ŭkrēshən}}, {{IPA|/ə.ˈkɹi.ʃən/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/V"kr\i:.S@n/}}
* {{rhymes|iːʃən}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act of increasing by natural growth; especially the increase of organic bodies by the internal [[accession]] of parts; organic growth.
#* '''1900''', [[w:Charles W. Chesnutt|Charles W. Chesnutt]], ''[[w:The House Behind the Cedars|The House Behind the Cedars]]'', Chapter I,
#*: There might have been a slight '''accretion''' of the moss and lichen on the shingled roof.
# The act of increasing, or the matter added, by an accession of parts [[externally]]; an [[extraneous]] addition; as, an ''accretion'' of earth.
#: ''A mineral ... augments not by grown, but by '''accretion'''.''
#* To strip off all the subordinate parts of his as a later '''accretion''' - [[w:George Cornewall Lewis|George Cornewall Lewis]]
# Something added externally to promote growth the external growth of an item.
# [[concretion]]; [[coherence]] of separate particles; as, the ''accretion'' of particles so as to form a solid mass.
# {{context|biology|lang=en}} A growing together of parts naturally separate, as of the fingers or toes.
# {{context|geology|lang=en}} The gradual increase of land by deposition of water-borne [[sediment]].
# {{context|legal|lang=en}} The [[adhering]] of property to something else, by which the owner of one thing becomes possessed of a right to another; generally, gain of land by the washing up of sand or sail from the sea or a river, or by a gradual [[recession]] of the water from the usual [[watermark]].
# {{context|legal|lang=en}} Gain to an heir or [[legatee]], failure of a [[coheir]] to the same succession, or a co-legatee of the same thing, to take his share.

